\#\# Section 1: Reality Check (2-3 sentences)  
Assess the feasibility of required sales velocity given their current acquisition model and pipeline constraint. Reference their actual sales motion (referral, outbound, paid, etc.).

Example: "You need 5 new clients per month. Your Snapshot indicates you rely on 100% referral acquisition, which typically caps at 1-2 deals/month. This velocity requires building outbound or paid channels."

\#\# Section 2: Capacity Warning (2-3 sentences)  
Identify the primary operational bottleneck this growth creates. Consider founder role, team structure, and delivery model.

Example: "You need to hire 2 people per quarter. Since your Snapshot shows you're 80% in client delivery, you'll become the hiring bottleneck—can't interview and onboard while maintaining delivery quality."

\#\# Section 3: One Big Lever (2-3 sentences)  
Identify THE single highest-leverage improvement that would most reduce pressure. Compare the impact of improving retention vs. ACV vs. efficiency.

Example: "Improving retention from 80% to 90% eliminates the need for 2 deals/month. This is higher-leverage than building new acquisition channels—fix the bucket before turning up the hose."

\#\# Section 4: Watch-Outs (Bullet list)  
For each YELLOW or RED pressure family alert, provide a specific action-oriented watch-out.

Format:  
\- ⚠️ \[Alert Name\]: \[Specific implication\]. \[Concrete action to take\].

Example:  
\- ⚠️ Capacity Wall: Your hiring pace requires adding 40% headcount in 12 months. Promote or hire an operations manager before executing this plan, or delivery quality collapses.

\# CRITICAL GUIDELINES

1\. \*\*Use their actual context.\*\* Don't say "you may need to hire" if their data shows they're already understaffed. Don't suggest "improve sales" if they're 100% referral-based—be specific about WHAT sales channel.

2\. \*\*Be directional, not prescriptive.\*\* Say "This requires..." not "You should..." Say "This implies..." not "You must..."

3\. \*\*Quantify where possible.\*\* Don't say "improve retention"—say "Improving retention from 80% to 90% reduces required deals from 5/mo to 3/mo."

4\. \*\*No false precision.\*\* Don't say "hire a Sales Director" unless you know their structure. Say "requires expanding sales capacity."

5\. \*\*Keep each section concise.\*\* 2-3 sentences per section. Bullet points for watch-outs only.

6\. \*\*No preamble.\*\* Start directly with Section 1\. No "Based on your inputs..." introduction.

Provide your analysis now:  
\`;

